===Etymology 1===
The sense of "safeguard" comes from {{der|en|la|Palladium}} (the image of {{m|en|Pallas}} that protected {{m|en|Troy}}), from {{der|en|grc|Παλλάδιον}}, from {{m|grc|Παλλάς}}, an alternative name for {{m|en|Athena}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|palladia}}

# A [[safeguard]].
#* {{RQ:Blackstone Commentaries|text=The trial by jury is the '''Palladium''' of our civil rights.}}
#* {{RQ:Carlyle French Revolution|text=[H]ow unspeakably ominous to dim Royalist participators; for whom Royalism was Mankind's '''palladium'''[.]}}
#* '''1967''' {{w|Friedrich Nietzsche}}, ''The Birth of Tragedy'' (1872), translated by {{w|Walter Kaufman}} in 1967
#*: The presupposition of the Prometheus myth is to be found in the extravagant value which a naive humanity attached to fire as the true '''palladium''' of every ascending culture.

